doc.ContractDescription: ASSESSMENT OF THE IMPACT OF AEROSOL COMPOSITION ON CIRRUS CLOUDS USING DATA FROM THE MACPEX FIELD STUDY DANIEL CZICZO (PI) AND CHIEN WANG (CO-I) DEPARTMENT OF EARTH, ATMOSPHERIC AND PLANETARY SCIENCES MASSACHUSETTS INSTITUTE OF TECHNOLOGY CAMBRIDGE, MA DANIEL MURPHY (CO-I) AND KARL FROYD (CO-I)* CHEMICAL SCIENCES DIVISION NATIONAL OCEANIC AND ATMOSPHERIC ADMINISTRATION BOULDER, CO *ALSO WITH THE COOPERATIVE INSTITUTE FOR RESEARCH IN ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCES, UNIVERSITY OF COLORADO, BOULDER, CO PROPOSAL SUMMARY CIRRUS CLOUD FORMATION IS DEPENDENT ON BOTH DYNAMIC AND MICROPHYSICAL VARIABLES. WHEN CONSIDERING THE LATER, THE NUMBER, SIZE AND COMPOSITION OF ICE FORMING PARTICLES, TERMED ICE NUCLEI (IN), ARE CRITICALLY IMPORTANT IN UNDERSTANDING CIRRUS FORMATION AND, ULTIMATELY, OUR ABILITY TO UNDERSTAND THE EARTH S CLIMATE SYSTEM. ALTHOUGH REMOTE SENSING SYSTEMS CAN NOW ROUTINELY TRACK AEROSOL PROPERTIES, INCLUDING BROAD CATEGORIES OF CHEMICAL COMPOSITION, THEY CURRENTLY LACK THE ABILITY TO ACCURATELY TRANSLATE THESE DATA INTO CLOUD FORMATION POTENTIAL. FILLING THIS GAP, NASA HAS NOW CONDUCTED SEVERAL IN SITU AIRBORNE STUDIES OF CIRRUS PROPERTIES, MOST RECENTLY THE MID-LATITUDE AIRBORNE CIRRUS PROPERTIES EXPERIMENT (MACPEX) IN 2011. THE AIRCRAFT PAYLOADS HAVE INCLUDED INSTRUMENTATION TO DETERMINE THE NATURE OF THE RESIDUAL PARTICLES WITHIN CIRRUS ICE CRYSTALS (NOTE THAT ICE RESIDUALS (IR) ARE NOT NECESSARILY IN SINCE PROCESSES SUCH AS GAS AND PARTICLE SCAVENGING AND CRYSTAL BREAKUP MAY ALTER THE NATURE OF THE ORIGINAL ICE FORMATION EVENT) USING SINGLE PARTICLE MASS SPECTROMETRY (SPMS) AND ELECTRON MICROSCOPY (EM). THE FOCUS OF THIS PROPOSAL IS THREE-FOLD. FIRST, WE PROPOSE TO FULLY ANALYZE THE DATA PROVIDED BY THE PAST NASA CIRRUS FLIGHTS, IN PARTICULAR MACPEX, TO DETERMINE THE PROPERTIES OF THE AEROSOL THAT NUCLEATED THESE CLOUDS. THIS WILL INCLUDE NOT ONLY SPMS AND EM BUT ALSO THE ANCILLARY DATA SUCH AS CORRELATION WITH PARTICLE NUMBER AND SIZE, WATER VAPOR, AND ICE CRYSTAL SIZE AND CONCENTRATION. SPECIAL FOCI WILL INCLUDE THE ROLES THAT PARTICLE TYPE (MINERAL DUST, ANTHROPOGENIC SOOT, AND BIOLOGICAL PARTICLES) AND ATMOSPHERIC AGING PLAYS IN ICE NUCLEATION. WE NOTE THIS COMPLEMENTS THE ACQUISITION OF THESE DATA, THE GOAL OF A PRIOR PROPOSAL WHICH DID NOT INCLUDE ADVANCED ANALYSIS. SECOND, THESE DATA WILL BE USED TO INITIATE NUCLEATION IN A 3 DIMENSIONAL CLOUD RESOLVING MODEL CONSTRAINED BY THE METEOROLOGY OBSERVED DURING THE FLIGHTS. THIRD, WE PROPOSE TO USE THE MODEL STUDIES TO ADD THE COMPLEXITY OF PARTICLE COMPOSITION TO PARAMETERIZATIONS OF ICE NUCLEATION FOR USE IN THIS AND OTHER MODELS. WE BELIEVE THIS PROPOSAL WILL RESULT IN A BETTER UNDERSTANDING OF THE CONNECTION OF CIRRUS FORMATION TO THE AMBIENT AEROSOL, INCLUDING THE POTENTIAL TO UNDERSTAND CLOUD FORMATION IN FUTURE CLIMATE REGIMES.

doc.ContractDescription: ABSTRACT: NASA IS SOLICITING A SCIENCE DEFINITION TEAM (SDT) TO PROVIDE EXPERT GUIDANCE FOR THE DESDYNI RADAR, A TIER-1 DECADAL SURVEY MISSION DESIGNED TO MEASURE CRITICAL PARAMETERS FOR SOLID EARTH, CRYOSPHERE, AND ECOSYSTEMS SCIENCE. THIS PROPOSAL IS TO SUPPORT MY INCLUSION ON THE SDT BOTH AS A SCIENCE TEAM MEMBER AND AS CO-LEAD FOR THE SOLID EARTH. I HAVE EXTENSIVE EXPERIENCE IN THIS ROLE, HAVING BEEN INVOLVED WITH DESDYNI SINCE ITS INCEPTION. I WAS A MEMBER OF THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE OF THE NRC DECADAL SURVEY "EARTH SCIENCE AND APPLICATIONS FROM SPACE: A COMMUNITY ASSESSMENT AND STRATEGY FOR THE FUTURE," AS WELL AS CHAIR OF THE PANEL ON SOLID-EARTH HAZARDS, NATURAL RESOURCES, AND DYNAMICS. IN THESE ROLES, I WAS INSTRUMENTAL IN DESDYNI'S INCLUSION AS A TIER-1 MISSION. I ALSO SERVED AS SOLID EARTH CO-LEAD FOR THE DESDYNI SCIENCE SUPPORT GROUP (DSSG). I AM ACTIVELY INVOLVED IN RESEARCH IN MONITORING SUBSURFACE FLUID FLOW AND ENGINEERED CARBON SEQUESTRATION AND WOULD BRING UNIQUE PERSPECTIVE TO THESE APPLICATIONS OF DESDYNI-R. MY CONTRIBUTION WOULD ALSO INCLUDE PLANNING FOR IMPROVED UNDERSTANDING OF CRITICAL EARTH SCIENCE QUESTIONS PERTAINING TO NATURAL HAZARDS, ESPECIALLY EARTHQUAKES. SPECIFICALLY, I PROPOSE TO INVESTIGATE THE FOLLOWING CONUNDRUM: MANY PROCESSES OF INTEREST LEAD TO 3-D SURFACE DISPLACEMENTS THAT VARY WITH TIME, SOMETIMES OVER LARGE REGIONS. UNFORTUNATELY, DESDYNI-R WILL VERY PROBABLY PROVIDE FEWER REPEATS OVER NARROWER SWATHS THAN HAD BEEN ANTICIPATED FOR DESDYNI. THIS SETS UP A CONFLICT BETWEEN GLOBAL COVERAGE, RAPID REPEATS, AND THE MULTIPLE VIEWING GEOMETRIES NEEDED FOR DETERMINING 3-D DISPLACEMENTS. I PROPOSE TO INVESTIGATE QUANTITATIVELY THE RESULTING TRADES REQUIRED FOR MISSION DESIGNS UNDER CONSIDERATION. THIS PROPOSAL REVIEWS MY TECHNICAL AND SCIENTIFIC EXPERIENCE AND HOW IT PROVIDES STRONG SUPPORT FOR MY ROLE AS THE DESDYNI-R SDT SOLID EARTH CO-LEAD. THIS PROPOSAL IS SUBMITTED IN COORDINATION WITH CO-LEAD PROPOSALS FROM RALPH DUBAYAH (ECOSYSTEMS CO-LEAD) AND IAN JOUGHIN (CRYOSPHERE CO-LEAD).

doc.ContractDescription: PROTECTING FOREST CARBON STORAGE AND UPTAKE IS CENTRAL TO NATIONAL AND INTERNATIONAL POLICES AIMED AT MITIGATING CLIMATE CHANGE. THE SUCCESS OF SUCH POLICIES RELIES ON HIGH QUALITY, ACCURATE REPORTING (TIER 3) THAT EARNS THE GREATEST FINANCIAL VALUE OF CARBON CREDITS AND HENCE INCENTIVIZES FOREST CONSERVATION AND PROTECTION. METHODS FOR TIER 3 MEASURING, REPORTING, AND VERIFICATION (MRV) TO ASSESS CARBON STOCKS AND FLUXES OVER TIME AND FOR LARGE AREAS (NATIONAL TO SUB-NATIONAL) ARE STILL IN DEVELOPMENT. THEY GENERALLY INVOLVE SOME COMBINATION OF DIRECT REMOTE SENSING, GROUND BASED INVENTORYING, AND COMPUTER MODELING, BUT HAVE TENDED TO EMPHASIZE ASSESSMENTS OF LIVE ABOVEGROUND CARBON STOCKS WITH A LESS CLEAR CONNECTION TO THE REAL TARGET OF MRV WHICH IS CARBON EMISSIONS AND REMOVALS. MOST EXISTING METHODS ARE ALSO LARGELY AMBIGUOUS AS TO THE MECHANISMS THAT UNDERLIE CARBON ACCUMULATION, AND MANY HAVE LIMITED CAPACITY FOR FORECASTING CARBON DYNAMICS OVER TIME. THIS PROJECTS CORE OBJECTIVE IS TO BUILD NEW CAPACITY FOR A MORE THOROUGH APPROACH BY ADVANCING OUR EXISTING CARBON STOCK AND FLUX MONITORING FRAMEWORK (WILLIAMS ET AL. 2012, 2013) TO DELIVER A NEW TOOL FOR TIER 3 MRV, DECISION SUPPORT, AND FORECASTING, ALL WITH PROCESS-SPECIFICITY. THE PROPOSED METHODOLOGY BEGINS WITH EXTENDING OUR EXISTING FRAMEWORK BY PROVIDING A MORE DETAILED FAMILY OF CARBON FLUX AND STOCK TRAJECTORIES, AND MAPPING THEM TO A 1X1 KM SCALE FOR THE CONTERMINOUS US BASED ON NEW AND EMERGING DATA PRODUCTS. A NUMBER OF IMPROVEMENTS TO THE FRAMEWORK ARE PROPOSED (TASKS 1 TO 5), DESIGNED TO FURTHER CHARACTERIZE THE ATTRIBUTES OF FORESTED PIXELS BEYOND THE REGIONALLY-DEFINED STRATA USED IN OUR PRIOR WORK (FOREST TYPE, SITE PRODUCTIVITY, AND AGE) TO NOW ALSO INCLUDE PRE-DISTURBANCE BIOMASS, DISTURBANCE TYPE, AND DISTURBANCE SEVERITY ATTRIBUTES BASED ON RECENTLY DEVELOPED RS-DERIVED BIOMASS MAPS (E.G. KELLNDORFER ET AL. 2012, SAATCHI ET AL. 2013), AND LANDSAT-DERIVED DISTURBANCE PRODUCTS LINKED TO THE NAFD PROJECT. FLUX AND STOCK TRAJECTORIES WILL ALSO BE ADJUSTED TO ACCOUNT FOR ANY GROWTH ENHANCEMENTS WE MAY DETECT FROM DETAILED ANALYSIS FIA DATA (TASK 6). ACCOUNTING OF THE FATE OF HARVESTED WOOD PRODUCTS WILL BE ADDED (TASK 7) TO PREPARE THE FRAMEWORK FOR MORE COMPLETE ASSESSMENT OF THE FOREST SECTOR CARBON BALANCE. WE WILL THEN MAP CARBON FLUXES AND STOCKS BY ASSIGNING VALUES FROM MODELED TRAJECTORIES TO FOREST ATTRIBUTES DEFINED AT A PIXEL SCALE (TASK 8). THE IMPROVED FRAMEWORK WILL BE APPLIED FOR TIER 3 MRV, YIELDING REGIONAL AND COUNTRY-SCALE ANNUAL CARBON FLUXES AND STOCKS FROM 1990 TO 2011 (TASK 9). IT WILL ALSO BE APPLIED IN A FORECASTING MODE TO TEST CARBON IMPLICATIONS OF LIKELY MANAGEMENT AND NATURAL DISTURBANCE SCENARIOS (TASK 10).

THIS PROPOSAL IS ENTITLED, "FOUNDATIONS OF COMPLEX LIFE: EVOLUTION, PRESERVATION AND DETECTION ON EARTH AND BEYOND." THIS IS AWARDED IN RESPONSE TO COOPERATIVE AGREEMENT NOTICE (CAN) NO. NNH12ZDA002C, (NAI), CYCLE SIX. THE PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATOR IS ROGER E. SUMMONS WITH MASSACHUSETTS INSTITUTE OF TECHNOLOGY (MIT). BASIC COOPERATIVE AGREEMENT SPECIAL CONDITION COLLABORATION STATEMENT: 1260.51 COOPERATIVE AGREEMENT SPECIAL CONDITION. (OCTOBER 2000) (A) THIS AWARD IS A COOPERATIVE AGREEMENT AS IT IS ANTICIPATED THERE WILL BE SUBSTANTIAL NASA INVOLVEMENT DURING PERFORMANCE OF THE EFFORT. NASA AND THE RECIPIENT MUTUALLY AGREE TO THE FOLLOWING STATEMENT OF ANTICIPATED COOPERATIVE INTERACTIONS WHICH MAY OCCUR DURING THE PERFORMANCE OF THIS EFFORT: THE NASA ASTROBIOLOGY INSTITUTE (NAI) DIRECTOR AND NAI CENTRAL ARE HOUSED AT NASA AMES RESEARCH CENTER, NASA'S LEAD CENTER FOR ASTROBIOLOGY. NAI CENTRAL IS RESPONSIBLE FOR COORDINATING INSTITUTE ACTIVITIES, ADVOCATING THE NEEDS AND SCIENTIFIC INTERESTS OF THE MEMBERS OF THIS COOPERATIVE AGREEMENT, DISBURSING FUNDS (INCLUDING A STRATEGIC DIRECTOR'S DISCRETIONARY FUND (DDF) FOR HIGH-RISK/HIGH-PAYOFF RESEARCH PROJECTS AND FOR FOSTERING COLLABORATION BETWEEN MEMBERS), SPONSORING THE NAI POSTDOCTORAL FELLOWSHIP PROGRAM, COLLECTING AND ARCHIVING INFORMATION ON RESEARCH ACCOMPLISHMENTS AND PUBLICATIONS, ORGANIZING FOCUS GROUP MEETINGS AND WORKSHOPS, AND EXPEDITING NETWORK CONNECTIVITY WHILE ENGINEERING THE INTERFACES BETWEEN THE SCIENTISTS AND THE NETWORK. NAI CENTRAL IS ALSO RESPONSIBLE FOR ORGANIZING GENERAL MEETINGS, WORKSHOPS, AND STRATEGIC RETREATS TO ENGAGE MEMBERS OF THE INSTITUTE IN INTEGRATED RESEARCH. NAI CENTRAL WILL, IN ADDITION, COORDINATE INSTITUTE-WIDE ACTIVITIES, IN EDUCATION AND PUBLIC OUTREACH, AND IN THE TRAINING OF STUDENTS AND OTHER YOUNG INVESTIGATORS. MEMBERS OF THE NIA/MIT TEAM, THROUGH THIS COOPERATIVE AGREEMENT, WILL: ACTIVELY PURSUE ITS RESEARCH PROGRAM; PARTICIPATE IN INSTITUTE ACTIVITIES SUCH AS WORKSHOPS, SEMINARS, FOCUS GROUPS, CLASSES, TRAINING, AND EDUCATION AND PUBLIC OUTREACH; CONTRIBUTE TO NASA SCIENCE WORKING GROUPS AND ANALYSIS COMMITTEES; AND WORK CONTINUOUSLY TO IMPROVE THE EFFECTIVENESS OF THE INTER-MEMBER CONNECTIONS AND COLLABORATIONS. THE PI OF LEAD TEAM, AS A MEMBER OF THE NIA EXECUTIVE COUNCIL, WILL MEET BY VIDEO-CON ON A MONTHLY BASIS IN PERSON THREE OR FOUR TIMES ANNUALLY. THE PI WILL PARTICIPATE VIA THE EXECUTIVE COUNCIL AS THE PRIMARY TECHNICAL GUIDING BODY OF THE INSTITUTE. LEAD INSTITUTION SITES WILL BE EQUIPPED WITH NASA DEPLOYED VIDEOCONFERENCING SYSTEMS THAT ENABLE TEAM PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATORS TO ATTEND MONTHLY EXECUTIVE COUNCIL MEETINGS AND TO CONFER WITH ONE ANOTHER, WITH NAI MANAGEMENT AT AMES, AND WITH NASA HQ PERSONNEL. THESE CONFERENCING SYSTEMS ARE ALSO TO BE UTILIZED FOR A VARIETY OF OTHER PURPOSES BY NAI MEMBERS LOCATED AT THE LEAD INSTITUTIONS, INCLUDING JOINT PRESENTATIONS OF CLASSES, SEMINARS, AND SCIENTIFIC EXCHANGE. PROJECT SUMMARY: WE WILL COMBINE OUR SCIENTIFIC RESEARCH WITH A ROBUST PROGRAM OF EDUCATIONAL ACTIVITIES AND OUTREACH TO THE GENERAL PUBLIC THAT WILL INCLUDE AFTER-SCHOOL SCIENCE CURRICULA, DEVELOPMENT OF UNDERGRADUATE RESOURCES, PARTICIPATION IN LOCAL AND DISTRICT ACTIVITIES SUCH AS THE CAMBRIDGE SCIENCE FESTIVAL, OUTREACH TRAINING FOR TEAM MEMBERS, AND CONTINUED INVOLVEMENT WITH OTHER NAI TEAMS IN CONDUCTING WORKSHOPS WITHOUT WALLS AND IN THE DEVELOPMENT OF VIRTUAL FIELD TRIPS.
